<subSubSection type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph pageNumber="456">
biology 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33867" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole microgyna Wheeler" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole microgyna Wheeler" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="456" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="microgyna">P. microgyna</taxonomicName>
appears to be a social parasite of 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33875" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole minutula Mayr" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole minutula Mayr" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="456" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="minutula">Pheidole minutula</taxonomicName>
. The latter species is abundant in the Amazonian and Guianan rainforests of South America, where it nests in the swollen leaf bases of the melastome understory shrub Maieta guianensis. In an earlier analysis (Wilson 1984b), I pointed out that microg)&gt;na may have its own workers, which are anatomically somewhat different from those of 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33875" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole minutula Mayr" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole minutula Mayr" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="456" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="minutula">minutula</taxonomicName>
, or workers identifiable as 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33875" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole minutula Mayr" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole minutula Mayr" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="456" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="minutula">minutula</taxonomicName>
. This circumstance suggests that 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33867" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole microgyna Wheeler" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole microgyna Wheeler" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="456" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="microgyna">microgyna</taxonomicName>
is a temporary social parasite of 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33875" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole minutula Mayr" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole minutula Mayr" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="456" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="minutula">minutula</taxonomicName>
or some related free-living species. The small size of the 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33867" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole microgyna Wheeler" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole microgyna Wheeler" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="456" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="microgyna">microgyna</taxonomicName>
queens also suggests such a life cycle. However, the status of this unusual form will not be solved until additional collections are made, preferably with field observations, allowing the taxonomy of the 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33875" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole minutula Mayr" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole minutula Mayr" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="456" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="minutula">minutula</taxonomicName>
complex to be more fully clarified.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
